(42, 5, 7, 20, 18, 24, 24, 'beckoned unto their partners', 'Friendship and Support in Crisis', 'This connection highlights the importance of friendship and support during challenging times. In Luke, the fishermen call for help, reflecting the idea in Proverbs that true friends are there in times of need.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 7, 45, 16, 2, 4, NULL, 'Support and Assistance in Ministry', 'This connection highlights the theme of mutual support in ministry. In Luke, the fishermen call for help, while in Romans, Paul urges the church to assist those in need, emphasizing the importance of collaboration and support among believers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 8, 23, 6, 5, 5, 'for I am a sinful man, O Lord', 'Recognition of Sinfulness', 'Both passages emphasize the awareness of personal sinfulness in the presence of God. Simon Peter''s declaration of being a ''sinful man'' parallels Isaiah''s lament of being ''undone'' due to his unclean lips.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 8, 18, 42, 5, 6, 'I am a sinful man, O Lord', 'Recognition of Sinfulness', 'Both passages emphasize a profound recognition of sinfulness in the presence of God. Simon Peter''s cry, ''Depart from me; for I am a sinful man,'' parallels Job''s response of self-abhorence and repentance after encountering God.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 8, 66, 1, 17, 17, 'Depart from me; for I am a sinful man', 'Fear and Reverence in Presence', 'Both passages emphasize a profound sense of fear and unworthiness in the presence of Jesus. Simon Peter''s plea to ''Depart from me; for I am a sinful man'' parallels the reaction of the figure in Revelation who ''fell at his feet as dead.''', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 8, 7, 13, 22, 22, 'for I am a sinful man, O Lord', 'Fear of Divine Encounter', 'Both passages emphasize the fear and recognition of human sinfulness in the presence of God. Simon Peter''s acknowledgment of being a ''sinful man'' parallels Manoah''s fear of death after seeing God, highlighting a common theme of human unworthiness before the divine.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 8, 18, 40, 4, 4, 'for I am a sinful man', 'Recognition of Sinfulness', 'Both passages emphasize a profound awareness of sinfulness in the presence of God. Simon Peter''s plea, ''Depart from me; for I am a sinful man,'' parallels Job''s admission of being ''vile,'' highlighting a common theme of humility before divine authority.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 8, 2, 20, 19, 19, 'for I am a sinful man, O Lord', 'Fear of Divine Presence', 'Both passages emphasize the fear and unworthiness felt in the presence of God. Simon Peter''s acknowledgment of being a ''sinful man'' parallels the Israelites'' fear of God''s voice, expressing a common theme of human inadequacy before the divine.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 8, 40, 2, 11, 11, 'fell down', 'Worship and Humility', 'This connection highlights the theme of humility in the presence of the divine. In both passages, individuals fall down before Jesus, acknowledging his holiness and their own unworthiness.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 9, 42, 4, 32, 32, 'astonished', 'Astonishment at Divine Power', 'This connection highlights the theme of astonishment in response to divine acts. Both passages emphasize the reaction of those witnessing Jesus'' power, whether through his teaching or miraculous deeds.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 9, 19, 8, 8, 8, NULL, 'Connection of Fish Imagery', 'This connection highlights the theme of fish in both passages. Luke 5:9 speaks of a miraculous catch of fish, while Psalms 8:8 mentions the fish of the sea, emphasizing God''s creation and dominion over aquatic life.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 9, 41, 9, 6, 6, 'astonished', 'Fear and Astonishment in Context', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear and astonishment in both passages. In Luke, the astonishment is due to the miraculous catch of fish, while in Mark, the fear arises from an overwhelming experience.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 9, 19, 8, 6, 6, 'astonished, and all that were with him', 'Dominion Over Creation', 'This connection highlights the theme of human dominion over creation. In Luke, the astonishment at the catch of fish reflects the authority given to humanity, as stated in Psalms, where all things are put under man''s feet.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 9, 42, 4, 36, 36, 'astonished', 'Authority and Astonishment', 'Both passages emphasize the reaction of those witnessing Jesus'' miraculous acts. In Luke 5:9, the astonishment at the catch of fish parallels the amazement at His authority in Luke 4:36.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 10, 40, 4, 19, 19, 'catch men', 'Call to Discipleship', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' call to his disciples to become ''fishers of men.'' This connection highlights the transformative mission that Jesus imparts to Simon and the sons of Zebedee.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 10, 40, 13, 47, 47, 'catch men', 'Fishing for Men and Kingdom Growth', 'This connection highlights the theme of gathering, as both passages use imagery related to fishing. In Luke, Jesus calls Simon to ''catch men,'' while Matthew describes the kingdom of heaven as a net that gathers ''of every kind.''', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 10, 26, 47, 9, 10, 'catch men', 'Connection of Fishing Imagery', 'This connection highlights the theme of fishing in both passages. Luke 5:10 speaks of catching men, while Ezekiel 47:9-10 describes a multitude of fish, emphasizing the significance of fishing as a metaphor for gathering and healing.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 10, 41, 1, 17, 17, 'catch men', 'Call to Discipleship', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' call to His disciples to become ''fishers of men.'' This connection highlights the transformative mission that Jesus imparts to Simon, James, and John as they leave their fishing profession.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
